Visible->True,
TaggingRules->{
 "ModificationHighlight" -> False, "ColorType" -> "", "LinkTrails" -> "", 
  "ExampleCounter" -> 1, 
  "Openers" -> {
   "PrimaryExamplesSection" -> Open, "ExampleSection" -> {"0" -> Open}}, 
  "NewStyles" -> True, "CitationPopupData" -> {"2021", ""}, "ShowCitation" -> 
  False, "RootCaptions" -> "", "HeaderCoreAreaLink" -> {}, 
  "Metadata" -> {
   "built" -> "{2026, 4, 12, 18, 0, 11.782001}", 
    "history" -> {"13", "", "", ""}, "context" -> "QuantumMob`Q3`", 
    "keywords" -> {"quantum oracle", "quantum algorithm"}, 
    "specialkeywords" -> {}, "tutorialcollectionlinks" -> {}, "index" -> True,
     "label" -> "Quantum Mob/ Q3 Tech Note", "language" -> "en", "paclet" -> 
    "QuantumMob/Q3", "status" -> "None", "summary" -> 
    "An oracle in computer science is a 'black box' entity that is able to \
produce a solution for any instance of a given problem without revealing how \
the solution was obtained. That being the case, the details of its \
implementation and its complexity are disregarded. Oracles are commonly used \
in computer science to theoretically classify problems in computational \
complexity theory, to analyze the complexity of algorithms, or to provide a \
way to solve problems. The concept of an oracle (i.e., black box) is a \
powerful tool in many other sciences as well that enables us to concentrate \
on what a device does without worrying about how to it is accomplished. In a \
decision problem, such as the Deutsch-Jozsa and related problems, we are \
supposed to figure out the unknown property by making queries to the oracle. \
In this document, we examine a quantum oracle, i.e., a quantum mechanical \
implementation of oracle. See also Section 4.2 of the Quantum Workbook \
(2022).", "synonyms" -> {}, "tabletags" -> {}, "title" -> "Quantum Oracle", 
    "titlemodifier" -> "", "metadescription" -> "", "windowtitle" -> 
    "Quantum Oracle", "type" -> "Tech Note", "uri" -> 
    "QuantumMob/Q3/tutorial/QuantumOracle"}},
